<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920317-0070</DOCNO><DOCID>920317-0070.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Nova Corp. of Alberta:   Firm Says It Plans to Close   Resin Plant in Massachusetts</HL><DATE>03/17/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   LABOR NVA T.NVA</CO><MS>ENERGY (ENE)</MS><IN>PETROLEUM (PET)PIPELINE OPERATORS (PIP)</IN><NS>LABOR, PERSONNEL ISSUES (LAB)PETROLEUM MARKET (PET)</NS><RE>CANADA (CN)MASSACHUSETTS (MA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Nova Corp. of Alberta said it plans to close itspolystyrene resin manufacturing facility in Leominster, Mass.   The gas pipeline and petrochemicals concern said theLeominster facility is no longer profitable, due to changesin the scale and efficiency of operations in the industry.The market for polystyrene and other chemicals produced byNova has been in a slump for the last two years.</LP><TEXT>   The Leominster plant has an annual capacity of 120 millionpounds, Nova said, but due to market conditions has beenproducing only 80 million to 90 million pounds of polystyreneresin a year. The closing, set for August, will put 60 Novaemployees out of work and reduce the company's totalpolystyrene resin capacity to 630 million pounds annually.   Nova, based in Calgary, Alberta, said the closing won'thave any impact on the company since it made provision forplant closings as part of a restructuring charge against its1991 earnings.</TEXT></DOC>